**FOOFOO RE**

Recommendation Engine Document Set

────────────────────────────────────

**DOC-10  ·  Technical Architecture**

Version 1.0  ·  Confidential  ·  June 2026

# **01  Architecture principles**

Six principles govern every technical decision in Foofoo. When two valid approaches conflict, the principles resolve the conflict. They are ordered by priority — the first principle outranks the last.

| **#** | **Principle** | **What it means in practice** | **What it rules out** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **1** | Free tier first | Every infrastructure choice must run on free tiers until 500 DAU. No paid infrastructure decision is valid before that milestone. | Any architecture that requires a paid service at launch — regardless of technical merit. |
| **2** | RE is sovereign | The Recommendation Engine is a standalone module. The app talks to RE only via the versioned API contract. No RE logic lives in the app codebase. | Embedding scoring weights, class codes, or cohort logic anywhere in the React Native app. |
| **3** | Offline by default | The user must be able to see today's plan without internet. The app should never show a blank screen when offline. | Architectures that require live API calls for basic plan display. |
| **4** | Security is not an afterthought | RLS on every table from the first migration. Service role key never in client code. Secrets only in environment variables. | Shortcuts like skipping RLS for 'internal' tables or storing API keys in source code. |
| **5** | Performance is a feature | 60fps gesture animations, < 3s plan generation, < 100ms swipe response. These are NFRs with the same priority as functional requirements. | Any UI component or network call that blocks the main JS thread during gesture animations. |
| **6** | Build for replacement | Every external service dependency must be replaceable with 2 weeks of engineering work. No proprietary lock-in for core product functionality. | Services where data migration is structurally impossible or data portability is not guaranteed. |

# **02  Tech stack — full selection with rationale**

## **Client layer**

| **Technology** | **Version** | **Role** | **Why selected** | **Why not alternatives** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **React Native** | 0.73+ (via Expo SDK 52+) | Mobile app runtime | Single codebase for iOS + Android. Best AI coding agent support (TypeScript). Largest ecosystem for mobile. | Flutter: fewer AI coding resources, Dart is less familiar. Native: separate iOS/Android codebases = 2× engineering cost. |
| **Expo SDK** | 52–56 (latest stable) | Build toolchain, native module management, OTA updates | Eliminates native build complexity. EAS handles cloud builds. Expo Go for instant device testing. No Xcode/Android Studio needed. | Bare React Native: requires local Xcode + Android Studio, complex native module management. Not viable for 2-person AI-assisted team. |
| **TypeScript** | 5.x (strict mode) | Type safety throughout the codebase | Catches bugs at compile time. Critical for a product with complex data shapes (RE request/response, household profiles, genome tags). | JavaScript: no type safety. Unacceptable for a product where a type error in allergen data can cause real harm. |
| **Expo Router** | v3 (file-based) | Navigation | File = route. Matches DOC-05 screen inventory exactly. Deep linking built in. Tab bar and stack navigation out of the box. | React Navigation: manual route definitions, no automatic deep link mapping. More boilerplate for same result. |
| **React Native Reanimated** | v3 | 60fps gesture animations | Runs animations on the UI thread, not the JS thread. The only way to achieve 60fps swipe card animations reliably on Android. | Animated API (default RN): runs on JS thread. Cannot guarantee 60fps. Unacceptable for the meal card swipe interaction. |
| **React Native Gesture Handler** | v2 | Gesture detection | Works with Reanimated v3. Handles swipe-reveal, carousel swipe, lock tap — all gestures the product relies on. | PanResponder (default RN): JS thread. Conflicts with scroll. Lower accuracy. |
| **TanStack Query** | v5 | Server state management, caching, offline | Handles caching, background refresh, stale-while-revalidate, and offline mode in one library. MMKV persister for plan caching. | Redux + RTK Query: more boilerplate. Context API: no caching or background refresh. Zustand alone: not designed for server state. |
| **Zustand** | v4 | Client/UI state | Lightweight, no boilerplate, no providers. Handles UI state (gesture state, tab selection, modal visibility) not managed by TanStack Query. | Redux: far too much boilerplate for a mobile app. MobX: less familiar to AI coding agents. |
| **MMKV** | latest | Local storage, plan cache, event queue | 10× faster than AsyncStorage. Synchronous reads (critical for offline plan display). Supports encryption (required for DPDP compliance on sensitive data). | AsyncStorage: async reads cause flicker on offline load. Not encrypted. |
| **expo-image** | latest | Dish photo display | Built-in blurhash placeholder support. Disk and memory caching. Avoids react-native-fast-image native module complexity. | react-native-fast-image: requires native build. expo-image achieves same result with Expo managed workflow. |

## **Backend layer**

| **Technology** | **Version** | **Role** | **Why selected** | **Why not alternatives** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Supabase** | Latest | PostgreSQL + Auth + Edge Functions + Storage + Realtime | Single platform for everything backend. Free tier: 500MB DB, 1GB storage, 50K MAU, 500K Edge Function invocations/month. PostgreSQL enables complex RE queries. | Firebase: NoSQL — cannot do the complex JOIN and aggregate queries the RE needs. Custom Node.js server: operational overhead, no free tier at this quality. |
| **PostgreSQL** | 15 (via Supabase) | Primary database | Full SQL for RE scoring, class-to-cohort joins, feature store queries. GIN indexes for full-text dish search. Row Level Security. | MySQL: weaker RLS support. MongoDB: NoSQL, cannot do relational RE queries efficiently. |
| **Supabase Edge Functions** | Deno runtime | RE module, event processing, onboarding, cron | Deploy alongside the database. Sub-100ms cold start. Access to DB via service role with RLS bypass for RE queries. TypeScript. | Separate Node.js/Python service: additional infrastructure, not on free tier. Vercel Edge Functions: no direct DB access. |
| **Supabase Auth** | Latest | User authentication | JWT built in. RLS integrates with auth.uid(). Email+password MVP. Social auth (Google/Apple) ready for Phase 0.5. | Firebase Auth: would require separate auth provider from DB. Custom JWT: implementation overhead, security risk. |
| **Supabase Storage** | Latest | Dish photo originals | Integrated with Supabase project. 1GB free. CDN-ready. RLS on buckets. | S3: separate AWS account, more expensive, no free tier equivalent. Cloudinary (storage): pricier at scale. |

## **External services**

| **Service** | **Free tier** | **Role** | **Replacement path** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **OneSignal** | Unlimited devices, basic segmentation | Push notification delivery (morning breakfast preview at 7 AM, prep reminders) | Firebase Cloud Messaging directly. 2 weeks to migrate. |
| **PostHog** | 1M events/month | Product analytics — DAU, funnels, retention, acceptance rate, session depth | Mixpanel or Amplitude. Data exportable via API. 2 weeks to migrate. |
| **Sentry** | 5K errors/month | Error monitoring, crash reports, performance monitoring | Datadog or self-hosted Glitchtip. 2 weeks to migrate. |
| **OpenWeatherMap** | 1K calls/day (60K/month) | Live weather data for RE contextual scoring (city-level, daily) | WeatherAPI.com or Tomorrow.io. Same data structure. 2 weeks to migrate. |
| **EAS (Expo)** | 30 builds/month free | Cloud builds for iOS and Android. App store submission. | Local builds with Xcode + Android Studio. 1 week to set up local pipeline. |
| **GitHub Actions** | 2,000 minutes/month free | CI/CD: typecheck, lint, tests, safety gate queries, build triggers | GitLab CI or CircleCI. 1 week to migrate pipeline. |
| **Cloudinary** | 25GB bandwidth/month | CDN delivery + on-the-fly image resizing (800×600 WebP for dish photos) | Supabase Storage + Image Transformation. 1 week to migrate CDN config. |

# **03  System architecture overview**

***The app is a dumb display client. All intelligence lives in the backend. The RE is a sovereign module.***

| **Layer** | **Components** | **Communicates with** | **Data direction** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Mobile client (React Native + Expo)** | 35 screens, Gesture Handler, Reanimated, TanStack Query cache, Zustand, MMKV offline store, OneSignal client | Supabase Auth (JWT), RE Edge Functions (HTTPS), Supabase REST (CRUD via anon key + RLS) | Sends: user events, onboarding data, plan interactions. Receives: meal slates, user profile, dish data. |
| **RE module (Supabase Edge Functions)** | POST /v1/recommendations, POST /v1/events, POST /v1/onboarding, GET /v1/plan, GET /v1/health | Supabase PostgreSQL (via service role), OpenWeatherMap API | Reads: cohort matrix, dish genome, user events, feature store. Writes: suggestion logs, plan cache. Reads: weather context. |
| **Database (PostgreSQL via Supabase)** | public schema (app data), re_engine schema (RE data) | Edge Functions (service role), Mobile client (anon key + RLS) | Stores all persistent state. RLS enforces row-level access control. |
| **Auth (Supabase Auth)** | JWT issuer, session manager, email+password, social (Phase 0.5) | Mobile client, Edge Functions (JWT verification) | Issues JWTs to client. Validates JWTs on all requests. |
| **Storage (Supabase Storage)** | dish-photos bucket (originals), CDN via Cloudinary | Mobile client (read via CDN URL) | Dish photos stored once. Served to client via Cloudinary CDN with on-the-fly resize. |
| **External services** | OneSignal, PostHog, Sentry, OpenWeatherMap | Edge Functions (server-side calls), Mobile client (client-side SDKs) | One-way: app sends events to PostHog/Sentry. Edge Functions fetch from OpenWeatherMap. |

## **Data flow — a morning plan request**

| **Step** | **Actor** | **Action** | **Data in** | **Data out** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **1** | Cron (11:30 PM UTC = 5 AM IST) | Morning cron triggers plan pre-generation for all active users | Active user list (last_active within 7 days) | Queues plan generation jobs |
| **2** | Edge Function: recommendations | Validates user context. Calls RE pipeline. | user_id, date (IST), city | Runs full RE pipeline (see RE-DOC-01) |
| **3** | RE pipeline | assign_persona → generate_class_plan → expand_dishes → score → mmr_rerank → safety_gate | cohort_matrix, dish_genome, user events | Ranked dish slate (8 per slot) + confidence score |
| **4** | Edge Function: recommendations | Writes plan to plan_cache table. Queues OneSignal notification. | Ranked slate | plan_cache row, OneSignal scheduled push |
| **5** | OneSignal | Delivers morning push at user's configured time (7 AM default) | Scheduled notification + breakfast dish name | Push notification to device |
| **6** | Mobile client | User taps notification → app opens → reads plan from plan_cache via TanStack Query | GET plan/{user_id}/{date} | Renders 3 meal cards in < 3s |
| **7** | Mobile client | User swipes, locks, accepts → interaction events fired | dish_id, event_type, meal_slot, context | POST /v1/events — logged to suggestion_logs |
| **8** | Edge Function: events | Logs event to suggestion_logs. Updates user's class affinity weights. | Event payload | Updated feature store (async, does not block UI) |

