# **13  Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)**

ADRs document significant technical decisions with their context and consequences. They are the institutional memory of why things are the way they are. Every engineer reads these before making changes to the architecture.

| **ADR-001 · React Native + Expo over Flutter or native** ***Status: Accepted*** **Context:** Two non-technical founders building with AI assistance (Claude Code). The product is a mobile app targeting Android (primary) and iOS. Budget is ₹25,000 — no external developers. **Decision:** Use React Native with Expo. TypeScript throughout. Expo SDK for native module management. EAS for cloud builds. **Consequences:** PRO: Largest AI coding agent support (TypeScript, React). Expo eliminates native build complexity. Single codebase. RISK: Some native features require custom native modules (mitigated by Expo's managed workflow). CON: Flutter would have better performance on low-end devices — accepted because RE runs server-side, not client-side. |
| --- |

| **ADR-002 · Supabase over Firebase or custom backend** ***Status: Accepted*** **Context:** Backend needed for: auth, relational database, file storage, server-side functions, and real-time (future). Budget constraint: free tier must be viable until 500 DAU. **Decision:** Use Supabase. PostgreSQL for the database. Edge Functions for RE and event processing. Supabase Auth for authentication. Supabase Storage for dish photos. **Consequences:** PRO: PostgreSQL is mandatory for RE queries — NoSQL (Firebase Firestore) cannot handle complex RE scoring joins and aggregations. Supabase free tier is more generous than Firebase Blaze for our use case. Open-source (self-hostable as exit strategy). RISK: Supabase is smaller than Firebase — less community support. Mitigated by excellent documentation. |
| --- |

| **ADR-003 · RE as Supabase Edge Functions (not separate microservice) at MVP** ***Status: Accepted*** **Context:** RE is specified as a standalone module with a versioned API contract. At MVP scale (< 500 DAU), a dedicated microservice adds operational overhead without benefit. Supabase Edge Functions can run the RE pipeline. **Decision:** Implement RE as Supabase Edge Functions at MVP. RE has its own schema (re_engine) and endpoints (/v1/recommendations etc.) that fulfil the module contract. Migration to a dedicated service is planned for Phase 3 if scale demands it. **Consequences:** PRO: Zero additional infrastructure. Runs adjacent to the database (low latency for RE queries). Deno TypeScript matches client TypeScript. CON: Edge Function cold start (~100ms) — mitigated by morning plan pre-generation cron. RISK: Edge Function timeout (150 seconds max in Supabase) — RE pipeline target is < 3s, well within limit. |
| --- |

| **ADR-004 · TanStack Query over Redux or Zustand for server state** ***Status: Accepted*** **Context:** The app needs: server data fetching with caching, background refresh, stale-while-revalidate, offline persistence, and request deduplication. Zustand is used for UI state but not designed for async server data. **Decision:** Use TanStack Query v5 for all server state. Configure MMKV persister for offline plan caching. Use Zustand for synchronous UI state only (gesture states, modal visibility). **Consequences:** PRO: Purpose-built for server state. MMKV persister is straightforward to configure. Automatic background refetch, error retry, and deduplication. CON: Another library to learn. JUSTIFIED: the alternative (manual fetch + Redux reducers + persist middleware) is 3× more code for the same result. |
| --- |

| **ADR-005 · MMKV over AsyncStorage for local persistence** ***Status: Accepted*** **Context:** The app requires: (1) synchronous reads for cached plan display on app open, (2) encrypted storage for sensitive user data (DPDP compliance), (3) fast event queue writes during gesture interactions. **Decision:** Use react-native-mmkv for all local persistence. Configure as TanStack Query persister. Use for interaction event queue during offline. Encrypt sensitive keys. **Consequences:** PRO: 10× faster than AsyncStorage. Synchronous read API (no await needed). Native encryption. CON: Requires Expo config plugin (adds complexity to managed workflow). MITIGATED: Expo MMKV plugin is well-maintained. |
| --- |

| **ADR-006 · Expo Router over React Navigation** ***Status: Accepted*** **Context:** Navigation library choice for a 35-screen app. Both are mature options. Deep linking is a requirement for push notifications. **Decision:** Use Expo Router v3. File-based routing matches DOC-05 screen inventory exactly. Deep linking configured automatically from route structure. **Consequences:** PRO: File = route maps directly to screen ID (H-01, OB-03, etc.). Deep links work automatically. Tab bar and nested stacks work out of the box. CON: Less community content than React Navigation (Expo Router is newer). RISK: Breaking changes in Expo Router v3 are possible — pin version. |
| --- |

| **ADR-007 · FlashList over FlatList for meal card lists** ***Status: Accepted*** **Context:** The home screen renders 3 meal cards. The search results screen renders dish rows. FlatList is the default React Native list component but has known performance issues on low-end Android devices. **Decision:** Use FlashList (@shopify/flash-list) for all scrollable lists of meal cards or dish rows. FlatList only for very short lists (< 5 items) where FlashList's estimatedItemSize is impractical. **Consequences:** PRO: FlashList recycles cells more aggressively. 5× less blank flash on fast scroll. Significantly better on Pixel 3a reference device. CON: estimatedItemSize must be tuned per list type. JUSTIFIED: performance on reference device is an NFR. |
| --- |

| **ADR-008 · OneSignal over direct FCM/APNs for push notifications** ***Status: Accepted*** **Context:** Push notifications are required for the morning habit loop. Implementing FCM (Firebase Cloud Messaging) and APNs directly requires managing two separate notification APIs plus scheduling logic. **Decision:** Use OneSignal. Single SDK for both Android and iOS. Scheduling, segmentation, and analytics built in. Free tier: unlimited devices with basic segmentation. **Consequences:** PRO: Single integration covers both platforms. Push scheduling (for 7 AM IST delivery) built into OneSignal dashboard. CON: Dependency on a third-party service. REPLACEMENT PATH: migrate to direct FCM/APNs + custom scheduling in Edge Functions. 2 weeks. |
| --- |

| **ADR-009 · TypeScript strict mode throughout** ***Status: Accepted*** **Context:** The product handles safety-critical data: allergen exclusions, dietary constraints, household member health profiles. A type error in this data could surface an allergen-containing dish to a user with a severe allergy. **Decision:** TypeScript strict mode enabled in tsconfig.json. No @ts-ignore comments. No any types except where TypeScript's inference is provably insufficient and the risk is documented. **Consequences:** PRO: Type safety catches the category of bugs that allergen data is most vulnerable to. Dish genome type definitions catch missing fields at compile time. CON: Slower development velocity (Claude Code must generate correct types first). JUSTIFIED: safety-critical data makes this non-negotiable. |
| --- |

